# Control Statements in Java

Control statements determine the flow of execution in a Java program. They are mainly classified into three categories:

## 1. Selection (Decision-Making) Statements

These statements execute different blocks of code based on conditions.

### `if` Statement

```java
int age = 20;

if (age >= 18) {
    System.out.println("Eligible to vote");
}
```

### `if-else` Statement

```java
int number = 10;

if (number % 2 == 0) {
    System.out.println("Even Number");
} else {
    System.out.println("Odd Number");
}
```

### `if-else-if` Ladder

```java
int marks = 85;

if (marks >= 90) {
    System.out.println("Grade A");
} else if (marks >= 75) {
    System.out.println("Grade B");
} else if (marks >= 50) {
    System.out.println("Grade C");
} else {
    System.out.println("Fail");
}
```

### `switch` Statement

```java
int day = 3;

switch (day) {
    case 1:
        System.out.println("Monday");
        break;
    case 2:
        System.out.println("Tuesday");
        break;
    case 3:
        System.out.println("Wednesday");
        break;
    default:
        System.out.println("Invalid Day");
}
```

---

## 2. Iteration (Looping) Statements

These statements repeatedly execute a block of code.

### `for` Loop

```java
for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
    System.out.println(i);
}
```

Output:

```
1
2
3
4
5
```

### `while` Loop

```java
int i = 1;

while (i <= 5) {
    System.out.println(i);
    i++;
}
```

### `do-while` Loop

The loop body executes at least once.

```java
int i = 1;

do {
    System.out.println(i);
    i++;
} while (i <= 5);
```

### Enhanced `for` Loop (For-Each)

```java
int[] numbers = {10, 20, 30, 40};

for (int num : numbers) {
    System.out.println(num);
}
```

---

## 3. Jump Statements

These statements transfer control from one part of the program to another.

### `break`

Terminates the loop immediately.

```java
for (int i = 1; i <= 10; i++) {
    if (i == 5) {
        break;
    }
    System.out.println(i);
}
```

Output:

```
1
2
3
4
```

### `continue`

Skips the current iteration and moves to the next iteration.

```java
for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
    if (i == 3) {
        continue;
    }
    System.out.println(i);
}
```

Output:

```
1
2
4
5
```

### `return`

Exits a method and optionally returns a value.

```java
public static int add(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
}
```

